00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:25.640
[YOTAM] So VeasyGuide was
created in a co-design process.

00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:28.611
It was a co-design with
three low vision participants,

00:03:28.636 --> 00:03:31.840
as well as my own experience
as a low vision individual.

00:03:32.213 --> 00:03:35.290
And we had three main questions
for the co-design process.

00:03:35.315 --> 00:03:38.480
The first is how do low vision
experience visual activities?

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:41.720
What challenges these
activities introduce,

00:03:41.720 --> 00:03:45.120
and also what makes these
activities easier to detect?

00:03:45.880 --> 00:03:48.880
For the sake of time, I'm going
to focus on the third question.

00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:51.720
So through the co-design
process and the iteration,

00:03:51.720 --> 00:03:55.720
we created those, design
implications for VeasyGuide.

00:03:55.720 --> 00:03:57.960
And ones the
VeasyGuide is based on,

00:03:57.960 --> 00:04:01.840
the first one is of course providing
visual access, with less effort.

00:04:01.840 --> 00:04:04.920
And we do that through highlights
and magnification or zoom.

00:04:05.720 --> 00:04:09.160
The second one is that visual
styles should be familiar to users.

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:11.800
And familiarity is something
that we achieve through

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:16.520
consistent styles throughout the video,
and also using familiar indicators.

00:04:16.520 --> 00:04:20.680
So for instance, in VeasyGuide we
use mouse pointers of different shapes.

00:04:22.680 --> 00:04:27.280
One more thing is predictability
of what, when and where to look.

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:32.240
So in VeasyGuide we introduce a
1.5 seconds pre-activity highlight.

00:04:32.240 --> 00:04:34.800
So the highlight shows
before an activity starts.

00:04:34.800 --> 00:04:39.573
And also we implement a box
shape highlight, which C1 mentioned:

00:04:39.598 --> 00:04:43.040
"The box tells me exactly
where and on what to look at."

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:46.040
So the box gives spatial
information as well.

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:50.240
And finally personalization
for different visual abilities.

00:04:50.240 --> 00:04:52.400
So different people have different needs.

00:04:52.400 --> 00:04:55.968
And so having personalization
as part of the design itself,

00:04:55.993 --> 00:05:00.000
allows VeasyGuide to be,
usable by many more people.

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:05.071
So these are the four design implications
that are the source of VeasyGuide.

00:05:05.096 --> 00:05:08.935
VeasyGuide itself is composed
of two main components

00:05:08.960 --> 00:05:12.575
and activity recognition pipeline,
which uses computer vision methods.

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:16.680
As well as a graph representation
of the visual changes,

00:05:16.680 --> 00:05:18.735
that allows us to detect activities.

00:05:18.759 --> 00:05:20.400
And activity visualization,

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:23.520
which is implemented as
a web based application,

00:05:23.520 --> 00:05:26.720
so activities can be changed
and customized on the fly.

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:30.040
And this is the base of VeasyGuide.

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:31.498
This is how VeasyGuide works.

00:05:32.040 --> 00:05:36.680
So getting back to our research
question, of how we improve it.

00:05:36.680 --> 00:05:40.520
So the question is will VeasyGuide improve
the experience of low vision people?

00:05:41.720 --> 00:05:45.428
So to evaluate VeasyGuide,
we used real world videos.

00:05:45.453 --> 00:05:47.920
From various creators, with various styles.

00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:52.280
And we had, recruited eight low
vision participants to basically

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:56.120
try and see if it can improve low
vision access to visual activities.

00:05:56.120 --> 00:06:00.280
But more than that, we also recruited
eight sighted participants to see

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:03.560
what will be the impact of
VeasyGuide on sighted people.

00:06:05.520 --> 00:06:07.080
And we had two main tasks.

00:06:07.080 --> 00:06:09.125
The first is a localization task,

00:06:09.150 --> 00:06:12.828
which allows us to focus on the visual
search problem specifically.

00:06:12.852 --> 00:06:14.760
And the second task is a viewing task,

00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:18.520
which allows us to explore the
experience of learning with VeasyGuide.

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:23.480
So, in this work we prioritize
external validity.

00:06:23.480 --> 00:06:27.040
So we allow participants to
use any of their assistive tools,

00:06:27.240 --> 00:06:30.240
such as magnifier, screen readers, etc.

00:06:31.031 --> 00:06:32.413
And here are some of the results.

00:06:32.438 --> 00:06:34.440
So, the first thing is that VeasyGuide

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:38.106
significantly allows low vision
people to notice more activities.

00:06:38.131 --> 00:06:44.360
So from a 60.9% accuracy,
we go up to 88.2%.

00:06:44.360 --> 00:06:46.280
So this is a significant improvement.

00:06:46.280 --> 00:06:48.960
And they do that with faster times.

00:06:48.960 --> 00:06:54.528
So we have a median of 1.37 seconds
using the baseline, so no VeasyGuide.

00:06:54.553 --> 00:06:59.160
Compared to 1.19 seconds
with VeasyGuide.

00:06:59.160 --> 00:07:01.680
So we can make it faster as well.

00:07:01.680 --> 00:07:04.440
But more than that, VeasyGuide
also significantly reduced

00:07:04.440 --> 00:07:06.785
the cognitive load that
is needed for learning.

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:11.455
So when all of the cognitive load metrics
that we tested effort, frustration,

00:07:11.480 --> 00:07:14.189
mental demand, physical
demand, and temporal demand

00:07:14.214 --> 00:07:16.183
VeasyGuide reduced significantly,

00:07:16.628 --> 00:07:17.862
The difficulty there.

00:07:18.573 --> 00:07:23.160
And more than that, qualitative
findings support our results.

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:26.542
So VeasyGuide makes it easier
to follow along the instructor.

00:07:27.378 --> 00:07:28.800
L2 mentioned,

00:07:28.825 --> 00:07:31.464
"I felt as if the
instructor had control, so

00:07:31.489 --> 00:07:33.856
