00:09:20.396 --> 00:09:26.000
So, beyond low vision people, VeasyGuide
also has the potential to enhance

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.203
the learning experience for others as well.

00:09:29.453 --> 00:09:30.336
To conclude,

00:09:30.361 --> 00:09:33.900
we discuss in the paper on
how can we design tools to support

00:09:33.925 --> 00:09:37.000
low vision users in tasks
that require visual search.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:39.960
So we reflect on our findings
from the co-design process

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:41.560
as well as the user study.

00:09:41.560 --> 00:09:45.720
And we found four key
concepts as a design framework.

00:09:46.090 --> 00:09:48.847
The first one is familiarity
with target visuals.

00:09:49.269 --> 00:09:53.000
The second is predictability
via spatial-temporal context.

00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:56.040
And personalization for changing needs.

00:09:56.040 --> 00:09:59.520
So all of these are extended
beyond the co-design findings.

00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:01.672
And we introduce another one,

00:10:01.697 --> 00:10:04.265
which is preserving user agency,

00:10:04.290 --> 00:10:06.765
which I want to explain
in a little bit more detail.

00:10:06.790 --> 00:10:10.320
So VeasyGuide basically gives
low vision learners the choice

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:13.400
to look, see, or follow the instructor.

00:10:13.756 --> 00:10:18.600
And with VeasyGuide they have the freedom
to always find the right place of focus.

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:22.120
So they can look anywhere else
in the slide and decide, actually,

00:10:22.120 --> 00:10:24.360
I want to see what the
instructor is talking about now.

00:10:24.360 --> 00:10:28.320
So it gave them the option, similar
to sighted people, to basically see

00:10:28.320 --> 00:10:32.437
whatever they want to see at the
